words: So when I was in high school I ran
track and cross country and we had kind of coaches that were a little bit crazy
and they like kind of monopolized
our life. And so the summer before my
senior year in high school they um, there were a few
parties between the boys and the girls team. There were some people drinking and some
people smoking and they found out about this half way through the cross
country season probably around November. And they really took it
out of proportion. They um they just really like
came down on us about it. And it was a really big thing in my high school. All of the other
teams found out. All of the other people in the high school knew about it. And it
was just embarrassing. It was really tough to go through and there
were so many meetings. And we felt like the enemy.
Um especially the seniors who they blamed for allowing this,
these parties to happen. And it was just kind of a really hard
time. It turned me off to track which I really had enjoyed
participating and I really had enjoyed running and trying my best to make
my times better and work harder. And I just didn't want to
run for the team anymore. There was a lot of animosity between those who were at
the parties and those who weren't at the parties. And there was a lot of guilt for
um you know making the coaches feel like it was their fault. Even though
there was no reason for them to feel like that.
I, it was a just very hard time. There was even
this one coach on the boy's team who threatened to hang us all which
was definitely not something that a coach should
be saying and he ended up getting released from our team
in the Spring for a different reason.
Um yeah but regardless of how I felt at the time
it, this event was kind of one of the reasons where I didn't pursue running in college.
I was supposed to run varsity for Capitol University and I decided not to
um probably the summer before um
I went to college. And it really allowed me to
focus on my future and not just on running.
So regardless of how I felt at the time of this event and how
hard it was for me to get through it, it really shaped the rest of my life.
